iteration: 1
analysis:
  per_query:
    Q1:
      current_time_ms: 73.9
      status: pass
      bottleneck: GenDB (80ms) is competitive with DuckDB (84ms) but has room for improvement through SIMD and better aggregation strategy
      root_cause: Code is already using parallel hash aggregation with 64 threads. The 4-6 group aggregation could use array-based aggregation instead of hash table. No SIMD is being used for filtering or aggregation. Minor floating-point precision issues suggest numerical instability.
    Q3:
      current_time_ms: 1351
      status: pass
      bottleneck: GenDB (1351ms) is 16.9x slower than DuckDB (80ms) - this is the CRITICAL bottleneck
      root_cause: "Three-way join is performing full hash table lookups without zone map pruning. Sequential filter on customer (30K out of 1.5M) happens first, then sequential scan of orders (1.5M rows) checking hash table membership, then lineitem scan (60M rows) with hash probe. No block skipping despite sorted data. The lineitem scan with hash probe on 60M rows dominates. Hash table lookups on filtered_orders are single-threaded (std::unordered_map is not thread-safe for concurrent reads during aggregation)."
    Q6:
      current_time_ms: 165
      status: pass
      bottleneck: GenDB (165ms) is 8.6x slower than DuckDB (19ms) despite being highly parallelizable
      root_cause: Simple scan+filter+aggregate query is not using SIMD for the 4 range predicates on 60M rows. The parallel implementation helps but memory bandwidth is limited. No zone map pruning on l_shipdate despite data being sorted by this column. Code evaluates all 4 predicates for every row sequentially (if-statement branches) instead of using SIMD comparison and mask operations. Predicate order is suboptimal - should evaluate most selective first.
  overall: "System has correct parallel execution infrastructure with 64 threads, but is missing critical optimizations: (1) Zone map pruning is completely absent despite sorted data and zone map metadata in storage design - this causes Q6 to scan 60M rows instead of <1M rows. (2) SIMD is not used anywhere despite AVX2/AVX512 availability - Q6 should process 8 comparisons per instruction. (3) Q3 suffers from inefficient join strategy with full lineitem scan and hash lookups instead of partitioned parallel join. (4) Q1 uses hash aggregation for only 4-6 groups where array-based aggregation would be 10x faster. GenDB is already faster than PostgreSQL (195x on Q1, 18.5x on Q3, 14.4x on Q6) but is 16.9x slower than DuckDB on Q3, which is unacceptable."
critical_fixes[0]:
performance_optimizations[8]{priority,target,bottleneck_category,operator,technique,description,expected_improvement,risk,requires_reingest}:
  1,Q6,io_bound,scan,Zone Map Block Skipping,"Q6 filters lineitem WHERE l_shipdate >= '1994-01-01' AND l_shipdate < '1995-01-01'. Data is sorted by l_shipdate (per storage design line 107: sort_order[1]: l_shipdate). Implement zone map pruning in queries/q6.cpp: (1) Load zone map metadata from gendb_dir/lineitem/l_shipdate.zonemap (min/max per 64K-row block). (2) Before parallel scan, evaluate which blocks can be skipped: skip block if block_max < date_start OR block_min >= date_end. (3) Create a skip list of valid block ranges. (4) Modify parallel_scalar_aggregate_filtered to only process rows in valid blocks. Expected: skip 90-95% of blocks (54-57M rows), reducing effective scan size from 60M to 3-6M rows. File: queries/q6.cpp, add zone map loading in execute_q6(), modify scan loop to iterate only valid blocks.","8-12x speedup (165ms → 14-21ms). Zone maps on sorted data typically achieve 10-100x pruning. With 1 year out of 7 year date range (~14% selectivity), expect to skip ~86% of blocks. Combined with existing parallelism, should reach parity with DuckDB (19ms).",low,false
  2,Q6,cpu_bound,filter,SIMD Vectorized Filtering,"Q6 evaluates 4 range predicates sequentially with branching. Implement AVX2 SIMD filtering in queries/q6.cpp: (1) Use _mm256_loadu_si256 to load 8 int32_t l_shipdate values. (2) Use _mm256_cmpgt_epi32 for date comparisons producing 8-way bitmasks. (3) Use _mm256_loadu_pd for 4 double values (l_discount, l_quantity, l_extendedprice) and _mm256_cmp_pd for FP comparisons. (4) Combine masks with _mm256_and_si256. (5) Use _mm256_maskload_pd to conditionally accumulate revenue. (6) Add compile flags: -mavx2 -mfma. Process 8 rows per iteration instead of 1, eliminating branch mispredictions. Combine with zone map pruning for maximum effect.","Additional 2-3x speedup after zone maps (14-21ms → 5-10ms), achieving 16-33x total speedup vs baseline. SIMD filtering typically provides 3-5x on simple predicates. Final time competitive with DuckDB.",medium,false
  3,Q3,io_bound,scan,Zone Map Block Skipping,"Q3 has three date filters: c_mktsegment = 'BUILDING' (customer), o_orderdate < '1995-03-15' (orders), l_shipdate > '1995-03-15' (lineitem). Data is sorted: customer by c_mktsegment (line 244), orders by o_orderdate (line 177), lineitem by l_shipdate (line 107). Implement zone map pruning for all three tables in queries/q3.cpp: (1) Load zone maps for customer.c_mktsegment, orders.o_orderdate, lineitem.l_shipdate. (2) Skip customer blocks where mktsegment zone doesn't contain 'BUILDING'. (3) Skip order blocks where block_min >= threshold. (4) Skip lineitem blocks where block_max <= threshold. Expected: customer scan reduces from 1.5M to ~300K (80% pruning), orders from 1.5M to ~500K (67% pruning), lineitem from 60M to ~40M (33% pruning). Files: queries/q3.cpp, modify all three sequential_scan calls.","3-5x speedup on join input processing (1351ms → 270-450ms). Zone maps reduce data volume before expensive join operations, amplifying benefits downstream.",low,false
  4,Q3,join_order,join,Partitioned Parallel Hash Join,"Q3 currently builds hash tables sequentially (filtered_customers: unordered_set, filtered_orders: unordered_map) then probes with lineitem. Problem: (1) Hash table builds are single-threaded. (2) Hash probes during parallel aggregation contend on shared unordered_map (not thread-safe for concurrent reads). (3) Lineitem scan touches 60M rows probing hash table 60M times. Solution: Implement partitioned parallel hash join in operators/hash_join.h: (1) Partition filtered_orders by hash(o_orderkey) % NUM_PARTITIONS into thread-local hash tables. (2) Partition lineitem scan: each thread processes 1/64th of lineitem, probes only relevant partition. (3) Use absl::flat_hash_map or std::unordered_map with pre-sizing to avoid rehashing. (4) Build phase: parallel build of customer and orders hash tables. (5) Probe phase: already parallel but partition-local reduces contention. Files: operators/hash_join.h (new partitioned join operator), queries/q3.cpp (use new operator).","Combined with zone maps: 2-3x additional speedup (270-450ms → 90-150ms). Partitioning eliminates hash table contention and improves cache locality. Total speedup vs baseline: 9-15x.",medium,false
  5,Q1,algorithm,aggregation,Array-Based Aggregation for Low Cardinality,"Q1 groups by (l_returnflag, l_linestatus) producing 4-6 groups (workload analysis line 73). Current implementation uses std::unordered_map<Q1GroupKey, Q1Agg> with hash computation for every row. For low cardinality, direct array indexing is 10-20x faster: (1) l_returnflag and l_linestatus are already uint8_t (3 values each: A,N,R for returnflag; F,O for linestatus). (2) Create fixed array: Q1Agg agg_table[256][256] = {}; (3) Replace hash table: local_agg[key] → agg_table[l_returnflag[i]][l_linestatus[i]]. (4) Merge phase: iterate 256*256 array instead of hash table iteration. (5) Output phase: collect non-zero entries. File: queries/q1.cpp, modify parallel_hash_aggregate_filtered to use array indexing.",1.5-2x speedup (74ms → 37-50ms). Eliminates hash computation overhead (currently ~40 cycles per row → 1 cycle). GenDB would be 2-4x faster than DuckDB on Q1.,low,false
  6,Q1,cpu_bound,aggregation,SIMD Aggregation,"Q1 computes 4 revenue expressions per row: sum_qty, sum_base_price, sum_disc_price (price * (1-disc)), sum_charge (price * (1-disc) * (1+tax)). After array-based aggregation, add SIMD: (1) Load 4 doubles per column using AVX2 (_mm256_loadu_pd). (2) Compute disc_price = _mm256_mul_pd(price, _mm256_sub_pd(ones, disc)). (3) Compute charge = _mm256_mul_pd(disc_price, _mm256_add_pd(ones, tax)). (4) Accumulate into SIMD registers, reduce once per chunk. (5) Process 4 rows per iteration. Combine with date filter SIMD for double benefit. Files: queries/q1.cpp, vectorize aggregate inner loop.","Additional 1.5-2x speedup after array-based agg (37-50ms → 20-30ms). Total speedup vs baseline: 2.5-3.7x. Final time 20-30ms vs DuckDB 84ms (3-4x faster).",medium,false
  7,Q3,cpu_bound,aggregation,Parallel Top-K Heap,"Q3 currently builds full hash aggregation (10K-100K groups per workload analysis), then uses single-threaded top-K heap. Optimize: (1) During parallel aggregation phase, each thread maintains local top-K heap (size 10). (2) Merge phase: combine 64 thread-local heaps (64*10 = 640 elements) into global top-10. (3) Saves building full global hash table of 10K-100K entries - only 640 entries to merge. Files: queries/q3.cpp, modify aggregation to maintain per-thread heaps, merge heaps instead of full hash tables.","1.3-1.5x additional speedup after join optimizations (90-150ms → 60-100ms). Reduces merge overhead from O(100K) to O(640). Total speedup vs baseline: 13-22x, reaching DuckDB's 80ms performance.",low,false
  8,ALL,cpu_bound,storage,Optimized Memory Hints (madvise),"Current mmap_column implementation likely uses default madvise settings. Optimize for each query's access pattern: (1) Q1 and Q6 (full scans): madvise(addr, size, MADV_SEQUENTIAL | MADV_WILLNEED) for aggressive prefetching. (2) Q3 hash probes: madvise(addr, size, MADV_RANDOM) to avoid wasteful sequential prefetch. (3) Add MADV_HUGEPAGE for large columns (lineitem: 60M rows = 480MB per double column). Files: storage/storage.cpp mmap_column(), add query-specific hints parameter.","10-20% speedup across all queries (reduces TLB misses and improves prefetch efficiency). Q1: 20-30ms → 16-24ms, Q3: 60-100ms → 48-80ms, Q6: 5-10ms → 4-8ms.",low,false
storage_changes[0]:
summary: "Iteration 1 is functionally correct but missing critical performance optimizations despite having good parallel infrastructure. TOP PRIORITY: Zone map block skipping for Q6 (8-12x speedup expected) and Q3 (3-5x speedup) - data is already sorted but zone maps are not implemented in query execution. SECOND PRIORITY: SIMD for Q6 filtering (additional 2-3x) and Q1 aggregation (1.5-2x) - CPU has AVX2/AVX512 but not being used. THIRD PRIORITY: Fix Q3 join strategy with partitioned parallel join (2-3x speedup) to eliminate hash table contention. After all optimizations: Q1 should be 20-30ms (3-4x faster than DuckDB's 84ms), Q3 should be 48-80ms (competitive with DuckDB's 80ms), Q6 should be 4-8ms (parity with DuckDB's 19ms). These are realistic targets based on workload characteristics and hardware capabilities (64 cores, AVX512, 44MB L3 cache)."